index 0000000..731bbb4
--- /dev/null
+++ b/SOLUTION.md
@@ -0,0 +1,18 @@
+# Solution
+
+Two bugs in `lrucache/cache.py`:
+
+1. **`get` didn't refresh recency.** The class docstring states both `get` and
+   `put` count as "use", but `get` never called `self._data.move_to_end(key)`.
+   This made `get` a no-op with respect to LRU ordering, so a recently-read
+   key could still be evicted as if it were the least-recently-used entry
+   (`test_get_refreshes_recency`). Fixed by moving the key to the end of the
+   `OrderedDict` on a successful, non-expired `get`.
+
+2. **`put` evicted on update of an existing key.** `put` checked
+   `len(self._data) >= self.capacity` before deciding whether to evict,
+   without checking whether `key` was already present. When updating an
+   *existing* key in a full cache, this incorrectly popped the actual
+   least-recently-used entry even though the update wouldn't grow the cache
+   size (`test_updating_existing_key_does_not_evict_others`). Fixed by only
+   evicting when `key not in self._data and len(self._data) >= self.capacity`.
